Energy Prices Prediction Challenge¶

This notebook analyzes energy price prediction using machine learning models on a dataset containing real-time prices, day-ahead prices, temperature, and time features. Time-series forecasting is a classical autoregressive problem due to its dependency on past data. Therefore, sequential algorithms like LSTM and Transformers are used.

The results of both LSTM and Transformer are comparable. Both models have around same number of parameters but transformer takes double the epochs to achieve same results. Thus, LSTM is preferred in our case.

In the end, results are visualized for both models and RMSE is discussed. Additionally, practical implications of this model in deployment are also discussed along with the suggestions.

Results¶

The models were trained for the given times and the following results were obtained.

Model Training Epochs Estimated Training Time Test set RMSE Test set MAPE (%)
LSTM 100 ~7 mins(RTX 4050 6 GB GPU) 3.8082 1932026739.73
Transformer 200 ~40 mins(RTX 4050 6 GB GPU) 3.7285 2034685364.99

LSTM was used for on-peak and off-peak comparison.

On Peak RMSE : 4.6138, Off Peak RMSE : 3.3986

Note: When Train = True is set, the models start training and replace the trained best models. If the above results are not obtained or complete training cannot be performed, please copy the models from saved_models_backup folder to saved_models(default location for saving models) to load the trained best models.

Few Important Things(Easy to miss)¶

  • Last 10% of the data is chosen as test set and no processing is performed on it, so as to mimick real-world scenario and avoid accidental leakage.
  • Outlier removal is only performed for the training data, not the testing data.
  • Only necessary features are used. Further testing can be performed with feature selection.
  • MAE loss is chosen so that model focuses on regular data more than the extremes.
  • MAPE is reported but it cannot be used for the data because of extremely small values resulting in astronomical high MAPE.

Effect of Temperature and Day-Ahead Prices on Real-time Prices¶

Day-Ahead Prices: Day-ahead prices are somewhat related to real-time prices, but the relationship is weaker than expected. Ideally, there should be a strong linear relationship, indicating accurate price prediction and bidding. However, the low r-squared value of 0.023 suggests little linear correlation.

Temperature: As expected, temperature has a positive effect on real-time prices. Higher temperatures lead to increased electricity usage for cooling, driving up real-time prices. However, the r-squared value of 0.01 indicates little linear relationship between temperature and real-time prices.

Trend Analysis Conclusion:¶

  • Hourly Seasonality: As expected, peak hours (4-10 PM) exhibited highest real-time prices, while off-peak hours (7 AM - 2 PM) had lowest prices. Unexpectedly, day-ahead prices were out-of-phase with real-time prices.

  • Daily Seasonality: Clear weekly pattern - peak prices on Tuesdays/Wednesdays, lowest on Sundays. Likely caused by higher midweek commercial/industrial demand and lower weekend demand.

  • Weekly Seasonality: Lowest prices in week 22 (late May), peaking in week 37 (early September), aligning with seasonal demand variations.

  • Yearly Trend: Real-time prices trended higher over the years.

Takeaways for Model Development:¶

  • Since average for real-time prices is trending higher over the years, we decide the inclusion of year as a feature. The absolute magnitude of the feauture is not important, rather relative magnitude is. Normalization will normalize the years to 0 - 1.

  • Since there is seasonality in daily and weekly patterns, we can give the model the day of the week and week of the year as features. However, final decision of the feature selection will be guided by both testing and these results.

Outlier Detection¶

The scatter plots of temperature and day-ahead prices suggest presence of outliers. Here we attempt to visualize the outliers and make some decision about them.

In [ ]:
years = pricing_data_df['year'].unique()
colors = plt.cm.viridis(np.linspace(0, 1, len(years)))

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
for year, color in zip(years, colors):
    subset = pricing_data_df[pricing_data_df['year'] == year]
    plt.scatter(subset['time_of_year'], subset['rt_price'], label=f'{year} Price', color=color, alpha=1, s=.2)
    moving_average = subset['rt_price'].rolling(window=300).mean()
    plt.plot(subset['time_of_year'], moving_average, label=f'{year} Moving Average', color=color, linewidth=1)
plt.xlabel("Time of the Year in Days")
plt.ylabel("Average Daily Real-time Price")
plt.title("Real-time Price with Outliers")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

The outlier detection indicates sustained abnormally high prices around day 50 in 2021 and abnormally low prices around day 300 in 2020. These outliers are likely due to random rare events, such as natural disasters or extreme temperatures, rather than erroneous data. As these behaviors are anomalies not observed in other years, they will be discarded as outliers. We will remove the bottom 0.5% and top 0.5% of the data, totaling 1% of outliers. Incorporating these extreme values would not enable the model to learn desirable behavior. In practical scenarios, we can include binary features for anomalous high/low events informed by real-life occurrences or features for events like earthquake predictions. Such features can help explain data variability and improve predictions.

Removing 0.5% outlier has improved the distribution of the data. Without outlier, the shape of the histogram is very leptokurtic. With outlier removal, the shape is more normal distribution and thus easier for the models to learn.

However, the outlier removal will be performed only on the training set, not the test set.

Outlier Detection and Removal¶

  • The decision is made to remove the top and bottom 0.5% of the real-time prices, considering them as outliers.
  • The outlier removal is performed only on the training set, not on the test set. Removing the outliers during the training helps the model to learn the general patterns of data, by not focusing on random rare outlier events. Further features that can explain the cause of the rare events can be provided to the model in the partical scenerio.

The command to remove outliers is disabled to report the metrics on unseen test dataset, during evaluation.

In [ ]:

    pricing_data_df = pricing_data_df[(pricing_data_df['rt_price'] >= lower_bound) & (pricing_data_df['rt_price'] <= upper_bound)]

Feature Selection¶

  • Feature Selection Strategy: Only necessary features are selected i.e. time_of_year(in days), temperature, day-ahead price, year and past real-time prices. 6 hours old data is provided and model is made to predict 6 hours real-time prices ahead. Real-time temperature is not included in the features.

  • Rationale Behind Feature Selection Strategy: Feature selection and manipulation is performed to select important features which explain the most variablity in the target data. This is a way to help the model understand complex patterns in data by providing data in a more 'digestable' way and removing the noise data. Modern deep learning algorithms can perform feature selection and manipulation themselves, but regularization and large amounts of data are needed to mitigate the multi-collinearity problem successfully. In our case, providing less features helped the model to predict better results. Further testing can be performed with proving more features, and more regularization but for this exercise we do not perform that.

Data Preparation¶

Three datasets are created: training, validation, and test (latest 10% of data). The target variable 'target_rt_price' is created by shifting 'rt_prices' by 24 timesteps (6 hours). Input features are a sequence of length 96 (seq_len=96) with 5 features (n_features=5), representing a 24-hour window.

Preprocessing:

  • No preprocessing on test set to avoid data leakage.
  • Training and validation sets are standardized using StandardScaler fit on training set.
  • Data converted to tensors. Dataloaders created for efficient training/evaluation.

The validation set is used to monitor overfitting during training, while the test set evaluates final model performance on unseen data, mimicking real-world scenarios.

In [ ]:
sequence_data = np.lib.stride_tricks.sliding_window_view(input_data.values, window_shape=(seq_len, input_data.shape[1])).squeeze(1)

X = sequence_data[:-1, :, :-1].astype('float32') # number_of_seqs, seq_len, features
Y = sequence_data[:-1, -timesteps_ahead, -1].astype('float32') # number_of_seqs, seq_len, 1

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = sklearn.model_selection.train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.1, shuffle=False)
In [ ]:
times_of_year = X_test[:, (seq_len-1), 1] # in days and their fractional part

# Calculating future prediction hours by adding 6, and wrap around using modulo 24
hours_of_day = ((times_of_year % 1) * 24 + 6) % 24

on_peak_hours = (hours_of_day >= 8) & (hours_of_day < 24)
off_peak_hours = ~on_peak_hours

X_test_on_peak = X_test[on_peak_hours]
X_test_off_peak = X_test[off_peak_hours]
y_test_on_peak = y_test[on_peak_hours]
y_test_off_peak = y_test[off_peak_hours]

X_test_on_peak = torch.tensor(X_test_on_peak, device=device)
X_test_off_peak = torch.tensor(X_test_off_peak, device=device)
y_test_on_peak = torch.tensor(y_test_on_peak, device=device)
y_test_off_peak = torch.tensor(y_test_off_peak, device=device)

Normalization and Sequencing¶

  • The dataset is split into training, validation, and test sets.
  • Target column 'target_rt_price' is added by shifting the current rt_prices by 24 timesteps(6 hours). This column is used as the target while a sequence of (seq_len=96, n_features=5) is used for input
  • Standard scaling is applied separately to the training and test sets using the StandardScaler from scikit-learn.
  • Multi-variate time-series models require the data to in the form of sequences. We create sequences of 96 timesteps(one day) to be fed into the model.
In [ ]:
# Applying seperate scaling parameters of train set on the test set

X_train_reshaped = X_train.reshape(-1, X_train.shape[2])

X_train = X_train_scaled.reshape(X_train.shape)

LSTM Model¶

The LSTM model is suited for time series forecasting, such as predicting energy prices, due to its ability to retain information over extended periods. This capability stems from its architecture, which includes memory cells and gates that regulate the flow of information. These gates help LSTMs to both capture long-term dependencies and ignore irrelevant data, a significant advantage in dealing with the fluctuations and trends typical in energy markets. This attribute allows the LSTM to outperform simpler models like GRUs and RNNs, which have more limited mechanisms for handling long-term dependencies, and even complex models like Transformers that may need large data for better generalization.

Now we will set up the LSTM model

Loss Function and Optimizer:¶

  • L1 Loss(MAE) is chosen over MSE as the loss function since MSE penalizes large errors more heavily, causing the model to overfocus on rare events. With most data concentrated around the mean, MAE ensures the model accurately predicts typical outputs by minimizing absolute errors across the entire range.
  • Adam optimizer is chosen because it uses momentum and adaptive learning rate, which helps accelerate convergence and maintains a steady training pace.

Transformer¶

The Transformer model, popularized by GPT-3, usually needs a lot of data to work well. Despite this, we're going to train a Transformer with a decoder setup and causal self-attention to see how it performs on our energy price data.

Conclusion¶

The results of both LSTM and Transformer are comparable. Both models have around same number of parameters but transformer takes double the epochs to achieve same results.

Further Ideas¶

Here we list the things that can be performed if we have more time:

  • Multiple Models: Multiple ensemble models can be trained and then their average can be taken as final results. Similaly, seperate models for on-peak and off-peak can be trained.
  • Feature Engineering: Different features can be tested like adding week_of_day and others. Similarly, more features can be generated like moving averages over different time periods to help the model make better prediction.
  • Outlier Identification: Outliers can be removed in a better way i.e. removing all data points for specific outlier events.
  • Incorporating ARIMA: Incorporating ARIMA (AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average) components or other traditional time series forecasting methods with deep learning models can yield a hybrid model that captures linear and non-linear relationships more effectively.
  • Different Model Architectures and Sizes: We only used only size of model for training. We can experiment with different sizes and architetures(maybe RNN with 4 times the cells of LSTM?). We could also try adding regularization like L2 regularization and dropout techniques.
  • Hyperparameters Experimentation: Different learning rates could also be tested.

Real-World Deployment Considerations¶

  • We observe long-term trends in data i.e. higher prices over the years. Due to this, we need to implement techniques to monitor data distribution drifts.
  • We observe that model's predictions get worse as we try to predict farther in time(close to the ending of the data). Constant model training is necessary for the model to learn the recent events.
  • As discussed earlier, the rare events are causing outliers in the data. More features are needed which can explain the cause of the data for better predictions in those rare events. They could be simple as two binary variables for over-supply/over-demand events, or they could also be detailed cause of the events like intensity of sun(which would impact the electricity supply and thus prices)
